:''This article is about the Quebec politician. For the former NHL player, see [[List of NHL one gamers#M]].''

'''Scott McKay''' (born c. [[1961]]) is the current leader of the [[Green Party of Quebec]], and is a former [[Montreal]] city councillor.<ref>CNEWS: [http://cnews.canoe.ca/CNEWS/Politics/2006/05/28/1602686-cp.html Green Party of Quebec rejects merger]</ref>
He was elected leader on [[May 28]], [[2006]].<ref>[http://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=fr&u=http://www.flambeaudelest.com/article-18357-Scott-McKay-elu-chef-du-Parti-vert-du-Quebec.html&sa=X&oi=translate&resnum=6&ct=result&prev=/search%3Fq%3D%2522Scott%2BMcKay%2522%252BQuebec%26start%3D20%26hl%3Den%26lr%3D%26sa%3DN  Scott McKay elected chief of the Green Party of Quebec] (Google Translation of [http://www.flambeaudelest.com/article-18357-Scott-McKay-elu-chef-du-Parti-vert-du-Quebec.html Scott McKay élu chef du Parti vert du Québec])</ref>

McKay was born to a [[francophone]] mother and an [[anglophone]] father in the city of [[Montréal-Est]].<ref>La Presse: Portrait de Scott McKay [http://www.cyberpresse.ca/article/20061017/CPACTUALITES/610170785&SearchID=73260136745614]</ref>

He was councillor for the district of [[Honoré Beaugrand]] from [[1986]] to [[1994]] under Mayor [[Jean Doré]].

He has completed a [[M.Sc.]] in Environmental sciences and is currently working in the field of water treatment. 

